I&#x27;ve also seen very simple object systems built purely using closures in Lisp. I can&#x27;t remember where I&#x27;ve seen it, but it usually involves the bank account example. Since no other Lisp features were involved,until you start glossing over with macros, this could be replicated in JS. It&#x27;d look strange but it&#x27;s certainly possible, e.g:<p><pre><code>  var savings = account(200);

  savings(&#x27;deposit&#x27;)(200);
  console.log(savings(&#x27;amount&#x27;)); // should print 400

  savings(&#x27;withdraw&#x27;)(200);
  console.log(savings(&#x27;amount&#x27;)); // should print 200
</code></pre>
If you can build an OO system in terms of lambdas and closures, does it mean the two are incompatible? I don&#x27;t think so.
